  "script": "Earth's orbit is filling up with junk, and we're getting close to a point of no return. There are now tens of thousands of satellites and millions of tiny debris fragments circling the planet at 17,000 miles an hour. At that speed, a fleck of paint hits like a bullet. Scientists warn about a chain reaction called Kessler syndrome: one collision makes more debris, which causes more collisions, until whole orbits become unusable. We launch more satellites every single week, packing the same lanes tighter and tighter. Lose those orbits and we lose GPS, weather forecasts, and the internet for half the planet. So who is actually cleaning any of this up?",
